@page "/blogs/using-linq-count-min-max-average-sum-to-aggregate-data"
@using LINQDemoComponents
@inherits BasePage

<Content FileName=@nameof(LINQAggregation) UseNewTableOfContentsMenu=true>
    <ContentBody>
        <What>
            <p>
                In this article, let's learn about how to use <Highlight>Count</Highlight>, <Highlight>Min</Highlight>, <Highlight>Max</Highlight>, 
                <Highlight>MinBy</Highlight>, <Highlight>MaxBy</Highlight>, <Highlight>Average</Highlight>, <Highlight>Sum</Highlight> 
                and <Highlight>Aggregate</Highlight> in <Highlight>LINQ</Highlight> in .NET.
            </p>

            <p>
                <strong>Note:</strong> If you have not done so already, I recommend you read the article on
                <NavLink href="blogs/using-linq-group-by-to-group-data" Match="NavLinkMatch.All">Using LINQ Group By to group data</NavLink>.
            </p>

            <p>
                When working with group of data we often need to do calculate some aggregate value out of it. With LINQ, the aggregate functions such as <Highlight>Count</Highlight>, 
                <Highlight>Min</Highlight>, <Highlight>Max</Highlight>, <Highlight>MinBy</Highlight>, <Highlight>MaxBy</Highlight>, 
                <Highlight>Average</Highlight>, <Highlight>Sum</Highlight> and <Highlight>Aggregate</Highlight> are used to calculate a <strong>single value
                from a property</strong>  in collection of objects. The Aggregate method is always applied after the query executes, which means it's already gotten the whole collection by applying 
                all the where clauses and everything, it retrieves the list, and then the method is applied.
            </p>

            <p>
                LINQ <Highlight>Aggregate</Highlight> functions is used to answer questions about collection such as 
            </p>

            <ul>
                <li>Finding the average sales happened during the season</li>
                <li>Validating the count of records</li>
                <li>Finding the total products value in a store</li>
                <li>Minimum / Maxmimum tempertaure recorded in a day</li>
            </ul>
        </What>

        <Why>
            <p>
                Working with groups of data often requires computing summary values — totals, averages, extremes. Without LINQ aggregate functions, 
                you'd resort to manual loops for each calculation. LINQ provides <Highlight>Count</Highlight>, <Highlight>Min</Highlight>, <Highlight>Max</Highlight>, 
                <Highlight>MinBy</Highlight>, <Highlight>MaxBy</Highlight>, <Highlight>Average</Highlight>, <Highlight>Sum</Highlight>, and <Highlight>Aggregate</Highlight> 
                to answer common data questions concisely and expressively.
            </p>
        </Why>

        <How>
            <h4 id="count">Count()</h4>

        <p>
            The <Highlight>Count()</Highlight> function returns the number of elements in a collection. This is a handy way to quickly determine the size of a collection, 
            and can be useful in a variety of scenarios, such as verifying that a list contains a minimum number of items before processing it further.
        </p>

        <CodeSnippet CssClass="language-csharp">
IEnumerable&lt;Product&gt; products = GetProducts();

//Method Syntax
int result = products.Count();

// OR

int result = products.Count(product =&gt; product.Color == "Black");
             
//Query Syntax
int result = (from product in products select product).Count();

// OR

int result = (from product in products select product).Count(product.Color == "Black");
        </CodeSnippet>

