        <h4 id="aggregate">Aggregate()</h4>

        <p>
            The <Highlight>Aggregate()</Highlight> function is the most flexible of the aggregate functions in LINQ, allowing you to perform custom aggregations on a 
            collection of data. For example, you could use Aggregate to find the product of all the numbers in a collection, or to concatenate all the strings in a list into a single 
            string.
        </p>

        <CodeSnippet CssClass="language-csharp">
List&lt;Product&gt; products = GetProducts();

//Method Syntax
decimal result = products
                 .Aggregate(0m, (sum, product) =&gt; sum += product.Price * product.Quantity);

//Query Syntax
decimal result = (from product in products
                 select product)
                 .Aggregate(0m, (sum, product) =&gt; sum += product.Price * product.Quantity);
        </CodeSnippet>

